+3+%281791%29&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.postdiploma.pl%2FConstENA5.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AConstitution" class="Z3988" about="#mwt124" id="mwBEA"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt124" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwBEE"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-44" id="cite_note-44"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-44" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-44" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt126" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Payne"},"first":{"wt":"Stanley G."},"authorlink":{"wt":"Stanley G. Payne"},"title":{"wt":"A History of Spain and Portugal: Eighteenth Century to Franco"},"url":{"wt":"http://libro.uca.edu/payne2/spainport2.htm"},"volume":{"wt":"2"},"year":{"wt":"1973"},"publisher":{"wt":"University of Wisconsin Press"},"location":{"wt":"Madison"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-299-06270-5"},"pages":{"wt":"432–433"},"quote":{"wt":"The Spanish pattern of conspiracy and revolt by liberal army officers ... was emulated in both Portugal and Italy. In the wake of Riego&apos;s successful rebellion, the first and only pronunciamiento in Italian history was carried out by liberal officers in the kingdom of the Two Sicilies. The Spanish-style military conspiracy also helped to inspire the beginning of the Russian revolutionary movement with the revolt of the [[Decembrist revolt|Decembrist army officers]] in 1825. Italian liberalism in 1820–1821 relied on junior officers and the provincial middle classes, essentially the same social base as in Spain. It even used a Hispanized political vocabulary, for it was led by &apos;&apos;giunte&apos;&apos; (juntas), appointed local &apos;&apos;capi politici&apos;&apos; (&apos;&apos;jefes políticos&apos;&apos;), used the terms of &apos;&apos;liberali&apos;&apos; and &apos;&apos;servili&apos;&apos; (emulating the Spanish word serviles applied to supporters of absolutism), and in the end talked of resisting by means of a &apos;&apos;guerrilla&apos;&apos;. For both Portuguese and Italian liberals of these years, the Spanish constitution of 1812 remained the standard document of reference."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBEI"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stanley_G._Payne" title="Stanley G. Payne" id="mwBEM">Payne, Stanley G.</a> (1973). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://libro.uca.edu/payne2/spainport2.htm" id="mwBEQ"><i id="mwBEU">A History of Spain and Portugal: Eighteenth Century to Franco</i></a>. <b id="mwBEY">2</b>. Madison: University of Wisconsin Press. pp.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwBEc"> </span>432–433. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwBEg">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwBEk"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-299-06270-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-299-06270-5" id="mwBEo">978-0-299-06270-5</a>. <q id="mwBEs">The Spanish pattern of conspiracy and revolt by liberal army officers ... was emulated in both Portugal and Italy. In the wake of Riego's successful rebellion, the first and only pronunciamiento in Italian history was carried out by liberal officers in the kingdom of the Two Sicilies. The Spanish-style military conspiracy also helped to inspire the beginning of the Russian revolutionary movement with the revolt of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Decembrist_revolt" title="Decembrist revolt" id="mwBEw">Decembrist army officers</a> in 1825. Italian liberalism in 1820–1821 relied on junior officers and the provincial middle classes, essentially the same social base as in Spain. It even used a Hispanized political vocabulary, for it was led by <i id="mwBE0">giunte</i> (juntas), appointed local <i id="mwBE4">capi politici</i> (<i id="mwBE8">jefes políticos</i>), used the terms of <i id="mwBFA">liberali</i> and <i id="mwBFE">servili</i> (emulating the Spanish word serviles applied to supporters of absolutism), and in the end talked of resisting by means of a <i id="mwBFI">guerrilla</i>. For both Portuguese and Italian liberals of these years, the Spanish constitution of 1812 remained the standard document of reference.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+History+of+Spain+and+Portugal%3A+Eighteenth+Century+to+Franco&amp;rft.place=Madison&amp;rft.pages=432-433&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Wisconsin+Press&amp;rft.date=1973&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-299-06270-5&amp;rft.aulast=Payne&amp;rft.aufirst=Stanley+G.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Flibro.uca.edu%2Fpayne2%2Fspainport2.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AConstitution" class="Z3988" about="#mwt126" id="mwBFM"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt126" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwBFQ"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-45" id="cite_note-45"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-45" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-45" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.canlii.org/en/ca/laws/stat/schedule-b-to-the-canada-act-1982-uk-1982-c-11/latest/schedule-b-to-the-canada-act-1982-uk-1982-c-11.html#sec60" id="mwBFU">Constitution Act, 1982, s. 60</a></span></li><li about="#cite_note-46" id="cite_note-46"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-46" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-46" class="mw-reference-text">The Constitutional Law Group, Canadian Constitutional Law. 3rd ed. Toronto: Emond Montgomery Publications Ltd., 2003, p. 5</span></li><li about="#cite_note-47" id="cite_note-47"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-47" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-47" class="mw-reference-text">Saul, John Ralston. <i id="mwBFY">The Doubter's Companion: A Dictionary of Aggressive Common Sense</i>. Toronto: Penguin, 1995.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-48" id="cite_note-48"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-48" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-48" class="mw-reference-text"><i id="mwBFc"> Aristotle, by Francesco Hayez</i></span></li><li about="#cite_note-49" id="cite_note-49"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-49" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-49" class="mw-reference-text"><i id="mwBFg"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.constitution.org/victoria/victoria_.htm" id="mwBFk">Relectiones</a></i>, Franciscus de Victoria (lect. 1532, first pub. 1557).</span></li><li about="#cite_note-50" id="cite_note-50"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-50" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-50" class="mw-reference-text"><i id="mwBFo"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./The_Law_of_War_and_Peace" title="The Law of War and Peace" id="mwBFs" class="mw-redirect">The Law of War and Peace</a></i>, Hugo Grotius (1625)</span></li><li about="#cite_note-51" id="cite_note-51"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-51" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-51" class="mw-reference-text"><i id="mwBFw"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.constitution.org/vct/vct.htm" id="mwBF0">Vindiciae Contra Tyrannos (Defense of Liberty Against Tyrants)</a></i>, "Junius Brutus" (Orig. Fr. 1581, Eng. tr. 1622, 1688)</span></li><li about="#cite_note-52" id="cite_note-52"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-52" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-52" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/webbin/gutbook/lookup?num=2053" id="mwBF4"><i id="mwBF8">The American Republic: its Constitution, Tendencies, and Destiny</i></a>, O.A. Brownson (1866)</span></li><li about="#cite_note-53" id="cite_note-53"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-53" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-53" class="mw-reference-text"><i id="mwBGA">Principles of Constitutional Design</i>, Donald S. Lutz (2006) <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt150" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"ISBN","href":"./Template:ISBN"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"0-521-86168-3"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwBGE"/><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" about="#mwt150" id="mwBGI">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt150" id="mwBGM"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/0-521-86168-3" title="Special:BookSources/0-521-86168-3" about="#mwt150" id="mwBGQ">0-521-86168-3</a></span></li><li about="#cite_note-54" id="cite_note-54"><a href="./Constitution#cite_ref-54" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-54" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.earlham.edu/~peters/writing/psa/" id="mwBGU">The Paradox of Self-Amendment</a>, by Peter Suber (1990) <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt154" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"t